In a three member set, connections throw "Could not find master" Exceptions when a slave drops out.

Configuration:
Server 1: Master (status state:1, health:1)
Server 2: Slave1 (status state:2, health:0)
Server 3: Slave2 (status state:2, health:1)

$m = new Mongo('mongodb://Master:27017/db', ['connect'=>true,'replicaSet'=>'set']);
$m->setSlaveOkay(true);

//throws cannot find master exception

This is odd since the only connection provided is to the master, which is up, healthy, and in all other ways indicating it's a master.

This is fixed immediately by invoking "rs.remove("Slave1")" on the master.  So it's definitely caused by a member of the set being down.

The Mongo constructor will not throw an exception if it fails to make a connection when specifying true for 'replicaSet'.  For example: 

try {
  $test = new Mongo("mongodb://foo:bar@example.com/foobar", array("timeout" => 200, 'connect' => true, 'replicaSet' => true));	
} catch(MongoConnectionException $e) {
  echo "Fail";	
}

If you run this code, it will not print "Fail". Removing the 'replicaSet' parameter will cause it to work correctly.

